{{British Flags}} This is a list of flags used in Northern Ireland.
==Official flags==
===Current=== These are the flags used by the British Government, the Northern Ireland Assembly and the Monarch in Northern Ireland.
{| border="2" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" style="margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse;" |- bgcolor="#efefef" ! width="110"|Flag!!width="100"|Date!!width="275"|Use!!width="275"|Description |- | {{ListFlag|Flag of the United Kingdom.svg}} ||align=center| Since 1801 || The [[Union Flag]], popularly known as the '''Union Jack''', is used as the [[flag of the United Kingdom]]. It is flown by the unionist community. || A superposition of the flags of [[Flag of England|England]], [[Flag of Scotland|Scotland]], and the [[Saint Patrick's Flag|St Patrick's Flag of Ireland]]. |- | {{ListFlag|Royal Standard of the United Kingdom.svg}} ||align=center| Since 1837 || The [[Royal Standard (United Kingdom)|Royal Standard]] of the United Kingdom. It is the banner of [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]] in her capacity as [[Queen of the United Kingdom]]. || Split into quadrants, the first and fourth quadrants contain three gold lions passant on a red field (representing [[Kingdom of England|England]]); the second quadrant contains a red lion rampant on a gold field (representing [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scotland]]); the third quadrant contains a gold harp on a blue field (representing [[Kingdom of Ireland|Ireland]]). |- | {{ListFlag|NI flax V1.png}} || 1998 || The flag of the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]]. || |}
===Former=== {| border="2" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" style="margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse;" |- bgcolor="#efefef" ! width="110"|Flag!!width="100"|Date!!width="250"|Use!!width="250"|Description |- | {{ListFlag|St Patrick's saltire.svg}} ||align=center| 1780s || [[St. Patrick's Saltire]], also known as the '''Cross of St Patrick''', after the [[patron saint]] of [[Ireland]]. The flag appears within the ''[[Union Flag]]'' now the official flag of the [[United Kingdom]]. It is used by the UFC, some Unionists, the [[Church of Ireland]] and is incorporated into symbols and emblems of various organisations and bodies throughout Ireland. || A red [[saltire]] on a white field. |- | {{ListFlag|Flag of the Lord Lieutenant of Ireland.svg}} ||align=center| 1801–1922 || Flag of the [[Lord Lieutenant of Ireland]]||A Union Jack [[Defacement (flag)|defaced]] with the [[Coat of arms of Ireland]]. |- | {{ListFlag|Flag of the Governor of Northern Ireland (1922-1973).svg}} ||align=center| 1922–1973 || Personal flag of the [[Governor of Northern Ireland]]. || A Union Jack [[Defacement (flag)|defaced]] with the [[Coat of arms of Northern Ireland]]. |- | {{ListFlag|Ulster banner.svg}} ||align=center| 1953–1972 || The '''[[Ulster Banner]]''', officially known as the '''Northern Ireland flag''',<ref>{{cite book |last=McCartney |first=Clem |year=1994 |title=Clashing Symbols?: A Report on the Use of Flags, Anthems and Other National Symbols in Northern Ireland |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=pIdnAAAAMAAJ&q=%22northern+ireland+flag%22&dq=%22northern+ireland+flag%22&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y |publisher=Queen's University of Belfast |page=2 |quote=The flag of the Government of Northern Ireland is often called 'the Ulster flag', but we have called it by its official name, the 'Northern Ireland flag'.}}</ref> was the flag of the former [[Executive Committee of the Privy Council of Northern Ireland|Government of Northern Ireland]]. It is used by the [[Unionism in Ireland|unionist]] community but no longer has any official status,<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-11431921 So you think you know the Northern Ireland flag?]</ref> although several sporting organisations such as [[FIFA]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Northern Ireland at FIFA.com |url=https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=nir/index.html |publisher=[[FIFA]] |accessdate=2007-11-28 }}</ref> the [[Commonwealth Games Federation]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Northern Ireland at the CGF|url=http://www.thecgf.com/countries/intro.asp?loc=NIR |publisher=[[Commonwealth Games Federation]] |accessdate=2007-11-30 }}</ref> and the [[PGA Tour]]<ref name="PGAProfile">{{cite web |title=Rory McIlroy PGA TOUR Profile - News, Stats, and Videos |url=https://www.pgatour.com/players/player.28237.rory-mcilroy.html |website=PGATour |publisher=[[PGA Tour]] |accessdate=2018-08-06 |language=en}}</ref> and media organisations such as [[ESPN]]<ref>{{cite web |title=ESPN.com - GOLF - Darren Clarke - Player Card |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/golf/players/profile?playerId=82 |publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures |accessdate=2007-11-28 }}</ref> currently use the flag to represent teams and athletes from Northern Ireland. || A red cross on a white field defaced with the [[Red Hand of Ulster]], crowned on a six pointed white star (representing the six counties in [[Northern Ireland]]). Based on the [[flag of Ulster]]. |- | {{ListFlag|Government Ensign of Northern Ireland (1929-1973).svg}} || align=center| 1929–1973 || [[Ensign]] of the former Northern Ireland government. || The [[blue ensign]] defaced with the letters GNI. Used on vessels of the Northern Ireland government. |}
==Local government flags==
{| border="2" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" style="margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse;" |- bgcolor="#efefef" ! width="110"|Flag!!width="100"|Date!!width="250"|Use!!width="250"|Description |- | {{ListFlag|Flag of Belfast.svg}} || ||The flag of the city of [[Belfast]]. || Banner of the arms of [[Belfast City Council]]. |}
==University flags==
{| border="2" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" style="margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse;" |- bgcolor="#efefef" ! width="110"|Flag!!width="100"|Date!!width="250"|Use!!width="250"|Description |- | {{ListFlag|QUB_flag.svg}} || 1910–present || Flag of [[Queen's University Belfast]] is a heraldic banner that is based on its coat of arms which were granted on 24 March 1910, two years after the establishment of the university. The arms are similar to those used by the [[Queen's University of Ireland]] which existed from 1850 to 1879.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qub.ac.uk/directorates/EstatesDirectorate/FileStore/UniversitysCoatsofArms/Filetoupload,18348,en.doc|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613205938/http://www.qub.ac.uk/directorates/EstatesDirectorate/FileStore/UniversitysCoatsofArms/Filetoupload,18348,en.doc|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2011-06-13|title=Page Not Found|work=qub.ac.uk}}</ref> || The banner is a [[Saint Patrick's Saltire]] that features a book, a sea horse, the [[Red Hand of Ulster]], a harp and a [[British crown]]. The book stands for the university, the sea horse represents Belfast, the Red Hand is for Ulster, the harp symbolises Ireland and the crown is for the [[British monarchy]]. The university's arms are blazoned as: "Per saltire azure and argent, on a saltire gules, between in chief an open book and in base a harp both proper, in dexter a hand couped of the third, and in sinister a sea-horse vert gorged with a mural crown of the fourth, an Imperial crown of the last". |- |}
